text.value:
 Okay, to declare that the input array to the addInArray method should have a length of 6, you can add a length check on the array parameter:

```java
public static String[] addInArray(String[] array, String value) {

  if(array.length != 6) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException("Array length must be 6"); 
  }

  // rest of method

}
```

This checks that the passed in array has a length of 6, and throws an IllegalArgumentException if it does not. 

You could also add a @param tag in the Javadoc:

```java 
/**
 * Adds a value to the array.
 * 
 * @param array the array to add to, must be length 6
 * @param value the value to add 
 */
public static String[] addInArray(String[] array, String value) {
  // ...
}
```

This documents that the array parameter must be of length 6.

So in summary, adding a check on the array length and/or documenting it in the Javadoc helps declare the expected array length in the method.
